  "observation": "Brainstorm triggered by plateau. 4 proposals generated.",
  "suggestion": "The plateau is caused by **premature convergence to a single evolutionary strategy in a static fitness landscape**. Your current system optimizes toward a stable attractor (the same body plan, the same decision logic, the same resource-to-reproduction ratio). Once all organisms cluster near that attractor, mutation becomes a random walk — most changes make fitness worse, so selection pressure vanishes. The system needs either *dynamic selection pressure* (predators, lifecycle forcing), *fragmented search space* (environmental niches), or *time-varying optimization targets* (coevolution). All three proposals introduce non-stationarity that prevents global convergence. The fitness landscape must move, or organisms can no longer improve by moving through it.; [medium] Introduce organism lifecycle stages with reproductive constraints: growth phase (immature, can't reproduce), reproductive window (limited duration), senescence (declining fitness). Death becomes inevitable, forcing genes to spread or die. — Current plateau suggests organisms have converged to static, immortal strategies optimized for pure existence. Lifecycle pressure creates temporal selection — survival alone is no longer sufficient. Organisms must reproduce *before* dying, forcing fundamentally different tradeoffs: growth speed vs reproduction delay, early reproduction vs late-life fitness. This breaks symmetry and opens new strategy space (r vs K selection, generation length strategies, pre-death resource dumping).; [hard] Introduce predatory organisms as a separate population competing in the same world. Predators eat organisms below a certain beauty threshold, creating predator-prey coevolutionary arms race. Beauty becomes a survival trait, not an aesthetic luxury. — Current system optimizes 0.5×survival + 0.3×beauty with no pressure linking them. Organisms can be ugly AND survive. Predators force directional selection: ugly organisms die. This creates dynamic, non-stationary fitness landscape where strategies that were optimal become dangerous. Arms race dynamics (predators evolve better hunting, prey evolve better evasion) drive continuous innovation. Plateau breaks because the fitness function is no longer constant-time but coevolving.; [medium] Partition world into distinct environmental zones (N regions) with different energy/resource distributions and local physics (e.g., zone A: high energy/low beauty pressure; zone B: scarce energy/high beauty pressure). Organisms born in a zone inherit that constraint unless they migrate (costly). — Plateau indicates convergence to a single global optimum. Environmental heterogeneity prevents global convergence by rewarding different strategies in different zones. Specialization becomes advantageous. Migration costs create biogeographic structure. Each zone evolves toward a local fitness peak with different tradeoff curves. Organisms can no longer all follow the same strategy. The population splits into ecological specialists, forcing higher population diversity and repeated innovation as zones change or boundaries shift.",
